{
  "doc_id": "39852",
  "text": "Although seasonality is less marked in male than in female, changes in testicular volume, hormonal profiles, sexual behaviour and semen quality that affect the reproductive performance of rams have been reported [CITATION_1] . In this sense, the treatment of rams with slow release implants of melatonin during the non-breeding season accounted for increased scrotal diameter and improved the reproductive performance of ewes inseminated during anoestrus with semen from these melatonin-implanted males. A direct beneficial action of melatonin on sperm motility [CITATION_2] ) and on other ram sperm characteristics during the non-breeding season has recently been demonstrated, with decreased apoptoticlike changes and modulating capacitation and fertilisation rates [CITATION_3] .",
